summary: a thing i noticed about Peter B. Parker is that everything about him is conveyed, through the aesthetics of the movie, in sorrow...
body:
a thing i noticed about Peter B. Parker is that everything about him is conveyed, through the aesthetics of the movie, in sorrow and exhaustion

his movements are a lot… not slower, not awkward, but weary. It takes emotional effort from him all the time. His colors are significantly more drab and gray than Miles or Gwen (who otherwise share his animation aesthetic, perhaps conveying that their universes are very akin). His expressions are mostly flat, even his comedic moments sound like he’s having to put a lot of effort into it.

He radiates exhaustion, wearinesss. He is a tired, broken man.

Until, that is

he puts on the mask.

and it’s not him having to be Peter B. Parker, professional wreck and burned out hero damaged by the lifestyle. He’s the amazing, the ultimate, the spectacular Spider-Man.

the instant he puts on the mask, everything bout him suddenly changes:

his drab colors are bright. his expressions go from ‘tired and doing my best to just slog through’ to the bright and animated you expect from Spider-Man. even his movements become a lot more flowing and fun

he is a sad and broken man who is just done with everything hurting, but the moment he puts on that mask, he’s your friendly neighborhood Spider-Man again
